{{DISPLAYTITLE:<span style="font-family:IM Fell English, Huiwen; color:white; text-shadow: 0 0 10px red"><b><b>Hydrolitis Plague</b></b></span>}}

<center>[[File:hpiconI.png|300px]]<div style="font-family:IM Fell English, Huiwen; color:white; text-shadow: 0 0 10px red"><big><big><big>Ring a-ring o' roses, A pocket full of posies,<br>Ashes, ashes, We all fall down.</big></big></big></div></center>

<br><br><br><br><br><br><br>

<big><big><big><big><big><big><big>Description</big></big></big></big></big></big></big><br>Entity 11, also known as Hydrolitis Plague, simply referred to as Hydrolitis, is a type of bacterium. It serves as the pathogen responsible for Hydromonia, a highly virulent infectious disease. In its natural environment, it lurks in untreated water bodies at specific aquatic levels and can spread through direct skin-to-skin contact. Depending on the location of the lesion, Hydromonia is generally classified into several types, such as pulmonary Hydromonia and septicaemic Hydromonia. 

Pulmonary Hydromonia mainly exhibits severe lung lesions. Patients typically experience coughing symptoms, which are often intense and frequent, and in severe cases, may be accompanied by hemoptysis. Meanwhile, breathing difficulties are also common, with patients feeling short of breath and experiencing aggravated shortness of breath upon physical activity. Even at rest, significant respiratory distress can occur, leading to a decrease in blood oxygen saturation and tissue hypoxia. The disease progresses extremely rapidly. Within a short period, the inflammatory range in the lung tissue continuously expands, and the alveoli are damaged, severely affecting the gas exchange function of the respiratory system and subsequently triggering a series of complications related to respiratory failure, posing a serious threat to the patient's life and health.

The main characteristic of Septicaemic Hydromonia is the massive reproduction of bacteria in the bloodstream. Once the disease occurs, the patient's body temperature rises sharply, with persistent high fever reaching 40℃ or even higher, accompanied by chills and shivering. As the disease progresses, the bacteria and their toxins circulating in the bloodstream trigger systemic infection symptoms, leading to vasodilation, a decrease in blood pressure, and subsequent shock. The patient may experience confusion and coma. This systemic infection causes severe and extensive damage to multiple organ systems of the body, including vital organs such as the heart, liver, and kidneys, which can lead to organ failure. It has an extremely high mortality rate and is an extremely dangerous type of infectious disease.

In-depth research and effective prevention and control of Hydrolitis Plague and the resulting Hydromonia are essential. We are studying the bacterium in depth and believe it will contribute to a deeper understanding of the biology, transmission and pathogenesis of the pathogen, providing a solid scientific basis for the development of targeted diagnostics, therapeutics and preventive vaccines.

Hydrolysis Plague exhibits a diverse range of transmission modalities. It possesses an extremely high level of biological contagiousness and has the characteristic of attaching to all animal or solid cells, thereby significantly enhancing its infection rate. In the case of individuals infected with Hydrolysis Plague, without the administration of appropriate medical treatment, fatality is an inescapable outcome. Nevertheless, if early and proper treatment is provided, the mortality rate can be decreased to approximately 80%.

Hydrolitis Plague exhibits an extremely high degree of instability and is prone to frequent mutations. Through extensive scientific research and surveillance, it has been conclusively established and is a matter of significant concern that certain mutated forms of the Hydrolitis Plague have acquired the ability to survive in water sources that have been subjected to only crude chemical sterilization procedures. This situation poses a serious threat to public health and water safety, as it implies that traditional and relatively simple chemical sterilization methods may not be sufficient to completely eradicate the risk of Hydrolitis Plague contamination in water supplies, potentially leading to widespread outbreaks and severe consequences for affected populations.


<div class="titleblock" style="background:var(--theme-page-background-color); border: 3px solid var(--theme-page-text-color);"><span class="titlebox" style="background:#000; border: 3px solid var(--theme-page-text-color);"><span style="text-shadow: 0em 0em 1.0em white, 0em 0em 1.0em white; color:#fff">Subject #1: [[Level 37]]</span></span>
<div class="hovering">[[File:l27hpI.png|link=|200px|right|<span style="font-family:Courier New;"><code>fig 1.0</code> A microscopic view of the Hydrolitis Plague in Level 37.</span>]]Multiple M.E.G. locations have reported the discovery of Hydrolitis Plague bacteria in filtered water. Upon investigation, we discovered that the water sources for these colonies all came from Level 37. In order to delve deeper into this anomaly and the harm it can pose, we conducted this study.
<br><br>We first took multiple samples of filtered water in Level 37 and brought them back to the specialized lab. In the laboratory, high-precision microbial detection equipment is used to isolate, purify and culture samples, and advanced gene sequencing technology is used to analyze the genetic structure of the bacterium to determine its species and characteristics, and then to study its survival mechanism in filtered water.<br><br>Surprisingly, it was found that this plague has the ability to survive in filtered water. This discovery implies that our drinking water safety will be severely threatened in the future. After a detailed analysis, it was revealed that the Hydrolitis Plague has mutated into an extreme bioaerogel form. In this state, pathogens can penetrate water source filters through an adaptive shell, thereby evading the sterilization effect of the filters.<br><br>Please remain calm. Since we have understood the principle, we are confident that a solution will be found in the near future. Until then, it is extremely necessary to carry out strict monitoring of all water sources, so as to detect potential risks in a timely manner and take corresponding measures to minimize the harm and impact that this plague may bring.<br><br>Note: The image on the right is the microscoped mutated Hydrolitis Plague.<br><br></div>
</div><br>

<br><br><br><br><br><br><br>
<big><big><big><big><big><big><big>Phases</big></big></big></big></big></big></big><br>
The phases of infection with this bacterium can be broadly divided into three phases.
<div style="background:#000; margin:auto; border:2px solid #fff; color:white; padding:1rem;"><big><big><big>Phase I:Acute Symptom Progression Phase</big></big></big><br>
The Acute Symptom Progression Phase is a crucial stage in the disease's development. It commences approximately 4 hours subsequent to the onset of the first symptoms and concludes after a period of around two days. During this phase, in addition to the symptoms that have been previously noted, individuals may encounter a diminution or absence of the senses of taste and smell. Skin discoloration may manifest, which could be an indication of underlying physiological alterations. Respiratory distress in the form of shortness of breath might be present, along with mental confusion and ocular irritation. Notably, hallucinatory experiences, often with thematic elements associated with the concepts of Backrooms or Frontrooms, can also be a part of this complex symptomatology. This phase requires close monitoring and appropriate medical intervention to manage the diverse and potentially serious manifestations.</div><br>
<div style="background:#000; margin:auto; border:2px solid #fff; color:white; padding:1rem;"><big><big><big>Phase II:Critical Decompensation Stage</big></big></big><br>
The Critical Decompensation Stage represents a significant deterioration in the patient's condition. Two days post-onset, in the absence of proper medical treatment, the persistent vomiting can precipitate a state of heavy dehydration, which in turn can have a cascading effect on multiple physiological systems. Respiratory function is severely compromised, rendering breathing an arduous and often labored task. Episodes of internal bleeding pose a serious threat, as they can lead to rapid blood loss and shock. The patient may experience profound delirium, indicative of the impact on the central nervous system. Concurrently, the bacterium initiates an aggressive assault on diverse anatomical regions, such as the brain, compromising neurological function; the lungs, impeding gas exchange; the limbs, potentially causing tissue necrosis; and the vital organs like the kidneys and liver, disrupting their essential metabolic and detoxification processes. Immediate and intensive medical intervention is imperative to arrest the progression and mitigate the potentially fatal consequences.</div><br>
<div style="background:#000; margin:auto; border:2px solid #fff; color:white; padding:1rem;"><big><big><big>Phase III:Terminal Lethal Phase</big></big></big><br>
The Terminal Lethal Phase marks the gravest and final stage of the illness. As the disease progresses, a significant escalation in cell death within the tissue is observed, which accelerates the onset of necrosis at an alarming rate. The internal bleeding not only persists but also exacerbates, spreading to multiple organs and severely disrupting their normal physiological functions. At this juncture, the patient's condition is irreversible, and medical intervention is rendered ineffective. The formation of blood clots around the veins and arteries is a common occurrence, giving rise to thrombosis. This thrombotic condition poses a substantial risk as it may progress to various heart diseases, further compromising the already failing cardiovascular system. In the most extreme and unfortunate circumstances, the Hydrolitis Plague invariably leads to the patient's demise, emphasizing the highly lethal nature of this terminal stage.</div>


<br><br><br><br><br><br><br>
<big><big><big><big><big><big><big>Survival Guides</big></big></big></big></big></big></big><br>The Backrooms Association of the Red Cross comprises experts in pathogens. Consequently, we have entrusted them with the task of formulating one or two survival guides. The remaining portion of the survival guide is currently being authored by The Backrooms Association of the Red Cross.
<div class="titleblock" style="background:rgba(139, 0, 0, 0.4); border: 3px solid var(--theme-page-text-color);"><span class="titlebox" style="background:rgba(139, 0, 0, 1); border: 3px solid var(--theme-page-text-color);"><span style="text-shadow: 0em 0em 1.0em white, 0em 0em 1.0em white; color:#fff">Survival Guide #1:</span></span>

<div class="hovering"><big><big><big><big><big><big><big>Stay away from water!</big></big></big></big></big></big></big><div style="background-color:#fff; border:1px solid #fff; width:100%"></div><br>
It is of utmost importance to maintain a safe distance from all types of water bodies. Unless it is an absolute necessity, refrain from setting foot in aquatic levels such as Level 37. As is widely known, these levels are prime breeding grounds for the Hydrolitis Plague. Once accidentally entered, the risk of infection is extremely high.<br><br>
However, in the event that due to an emergency situation, you have no choice but to enter such levels, there is no need to worry unduly! Our outposts can provide you with high-quality protective gear. This protective clothing is developed using advanced technology and can offer excellent protection against the vast majority of pathogens in the Backrooms, be it tiny and elusive bacteria, cunning and variable viruses, stealthy fungi, stubborn parasites, and even certain dangerous bioweapons, ensuring a safe exploration journey for you!
<br><br>It should be particularly noted that although some M.E.G. outposts also sell protective equipment, most of them are simple protective suits with uneven quality and can only deal with certain dangerous situations. It is recommended that you prioritize our professional protective clothing to obtain more comprehensive and reliable protection.
<br><br>If you find yourself already in one of these dangerous levels, do not panic! Immediately seek the nearest medical outpost for a comprehensive health check after a safe evacuation. Our medical outposts are fully equipped with facilities and sufficient medicines, and the professional medical team is highly experienced. Groups such as A.E.G. and M.E.G. will also go all out to assist, ensuring that your health condition is properly evaluated and handled.

- The Backrooms Association of the Red Cross
<br><br><br><br><br><br>
